  "title": "Nidiaci Community Garden",
  "story": [
    {
      "url": "https://firenzemoms4moms.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/2-nidiaci-from-above.jpg?w=639",
      "text": "Nidiaci behind Carmine church in Florence. [https://firenzemoms4moms.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/2-nidiaci-from-above.jpg?w=639 source]",
      "type": "image",
      "id": "cf79957c68bd1693"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fdd72ee0c542ee0f",
      "text": "It is called a \"garden,\" but it is way more: a neighborhood gathering spot, playground, parents' support group, soccer camp, place for music lessons, and green oasis in the busy city center of Florence, [[Italy]]. \n\nNidiaci Community Garden is not managed by city agencies, but is stewarded by the parents of the Oltrarno neighborhood, who manage this rare place for children. It is: "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "8cd4d4a0a551b3ab",
      "text": "<blockquote>\nthe only neighborhood of the [city] center not yet completely overwhelmed by pubcrawling and fashion shops."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "52e5de4d28213ec4",
      "text": "This is quite an achievement for a part of Florence that attracts millions of tourists each year to restaurants and nightlife, and that is pressured by intense gentrification. The area is clogged with traffic-infested roads, students who live in nearby  dormitories, and encircled by a wasteland of motorways, factories, the airport and an incinerator."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "efb846e9c8deb856",
      "text": "In a short history of The Nidiaci as a commons in an urban context, resident Miguel Martinez wrote in 2016:"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "aae233afc691e4b1",
      "text": "\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "7d4648a76c97ae33",
      "text": "<blockquote>\n \"By keeping social ties and community solidarity alive in one of Europe's most symbolic historic districts, we are an element of resistance to this design of things.\"\n</blockquote>"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dd886f962792a07f",
      "text": "# Legal Status and Location"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4d4f5f0dce765593",
      "text": "In 1920, the American Red Cross gave funds \"to an\nEntity\" which \"should deal with popular instruction and education, with special attention to children.\" The sum was invested in the purchase of this garden and buildings around it. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1a0a396d2f3ef6c5",
      "text": "These origins were largely forgotten until the founding legal documents were rediscovered by neighborhood residents. That spurred a neighborhood campaign against developers and city officials to establish the legal basis for reviving the children's garden, and then to persuade city authorities to permit residents to manage the place themselves."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "7589e58503a0672c",
      "text": "xxxxx"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "34785ce921da77a6",
      "text": "# How did it start? "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "f55c16f46da9f224",
      "text": "Even though the urban plot that comprises the garden area was formally public property, it was neglected by city authorities for years. Part of land  fell into the hands of real estate speculators, who tried to turn adjacent buildings into flats and the garden into a parking lot. This development led to many demonstrations and petitions by neighborhood residents. "
    },
    {
      "type": "html",
      "id": "7424592204bb3fa7",
      "text": "In 2011, Matteo Renzi ([https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matteo_Renzi wiki]), then Mayor of Florence, responded that saving the area was for him an \"absolute and irrevocable priority.\" But one year later, the roofed area was closed down and the children were driven out. The families of San Frediano (the neighborhood's name) got together and finally obtained the keys to the part of the garden still in public hands.\n "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "46b61bcfb6925803",
      "text": "# How is the garden managed?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "be5ee908c7775392",
      "text": "Neighbourhood residents set up a properly registered association, to make a legal body entitled to sign a four year \"convention\" with the municipality in order to manage, for free, the area, a convention which has recently (in 2017) been renewed."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7376b9e77387253e",
      "text": "While much of the area is used as a playground, an important feature of the \"garden\" is that neighborhood residents themselves can decide how the space should be used. Some of those activities include:\n- Hosting the only self-managed football school in town, where children learn to enjoy playing and not\njust winning;\n- English lessons by a British writer;\n- Violin lessons by a Portuguese musician;\n- Open exchanges of children's clothes for free by parents, to avoid waste;\n- Managing a small community garden;\n- Work on monitoring pollution and traffic using equipment provided by the National Research Council;\n- singing lessons with an opera singer\n- the chance to organise birthday parties for children in a very cramped area, where parents have to pay considerable sums to rent space for parties\n- and much else."
    },
    {
      "text": "<div style=\"\n  padding: 12px;\n  background:#eee;\n  width:96%;\n  align=centered;\">\n\n<img style=\"\n  display:block;\n  margin:auto;\n  width:100%;\"\n  src=\"https://firenzemoms4moms.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/3-opening-nidiaci-feast.jpg?w=510&amp;h=339\">\n\n<p class=caption>\n  A typical \"garden\" activity.\n  [https://firenzemoms4moms.files.wordpress.com/2014/03/3-opening-nidiaci-feast.jpg?w=510&amp;h=339 source]\n</p>\n</div>\n",
      "type": "html",
