    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "d18d3472ad6ba440",
      "item": {
        "type": "html",
        "id": "d18d3472ad6ba440",
        "text": "In 1920, the American Red Cross gave funds \"to an\nEntity\" which \"should deal with popular instruction and education, with special attention to children.\" The sum was invested in the purchase of this garden and buildings around it. The financial and organizational origins of the Nidiaci Garden had been largely forgotten. It took a concerted effort by neighborhood residents to establish the legal basis for reviving the children's garden (over and against the claims of real estate developers), and then to persuade city authorities to permit residents to manage the garden themselves.\n"
      },
      "date": 1505327066584
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "d7d7c16a1c7fcb8d",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "d7d7c16a1c7fcb8d",
        "text": "# [[Dimensions of Commoning]]"
      },
      "date": 1505327075816
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
        "text": "The Nidiaci Community Garden is a strong and relatively rare example of a park managed directly and extensively by commoners. (Although, the [Potato Park] in Peru is another kind of \"park\" managed by commoners.) In their joint management of the Nidiaci garden, residents show their desire to [[Cultivate Shared Purpose & Values]]. They recognize that this is a collective enterprise that requires an [Ubuntu-Rationality] (although they don't use that term!), which also serves to [[Strengthen the Nested-I]].\n\nThere is no strict calculation of work performed with benefits received; the garden can only run if residents [[Decouple Giving & Taking]]. While there are competing claims on the space at specific times, residents are able to [[Ensure Fair Abundance]] for all. \n\nIn managing the garden, residents [[Practice Gentle Reciprocity]]. Activities are for free or, when costs must he paid, co-financed by voluntary contributions. By helping children spend time outdoors, one might say that the garden helps [[Deepen Interdependency on Nature]] in modest ways (which is certainly more necessary in a crowded city).    \n\nWhile the city administration might otherwise treat the park like any other city park, the ability of the neighborhood to manage their own garden reflects a willingness to [[Trust Situated Knowing]] and to [[Be Creatively Adaptive]]. The garden itself provides a space for parents to engage more fully with their children and with other parents -- i.e., to [[Honor Care & Time]].\n\n--More on [[Preserve Relationships in Addressing Conflicts]]"
      },
      "date": 1505327701901
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "4db93825b2d37094"
      },
      "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
      "type": "add",
      "after": "3ec710271c321a79",
      "date": 1505327720088
    },
