      "item": {
        "type": "html",
        "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
        "text": "There is no strict calculation of work performed with benefits received; the garden can only run if residents [[Decouple Giving & Taking]]. While there are competing claims on the space at specific times, residents are able to [[Ensure Fair Abundance]] for all. \n\nIn managing the garden, residents [[Practice Gentle Reciprocity]]. Activities are for free or, when costs must he paid, co-financed by voluntary contributions. By helping children spend time outdoors, one might say that the garden helps [[Deepen Interdependency on Nature]] in modest ways (which is certainly more necessary in a crowded city).    \n<p>\nWhile the city administration might otherwise treat the park like any other city park, the ability of the neighborhood to manage their own garden reflects a willingness to [[Trust Situated Knowing]] and to [[Be Creatively Adaptive]]. The garden itself provides a space for parents to engage more fully with their children and with other parents -- i.e., to [[Honor Care & Time]].\n\n--More on [[Preserve Relationships in Addressing Conflicts]]"
