      "item": {
        "type": "html",
        "id": "d6f9b88cb6b3fb18",
        "text": "In its peer governance of the garden, neighborhood residents clearly wish to [[separate Commoning & Commerce]] and [[Develop Shared Purpose & Values]].  But they also [[Set Semi-Permeable Boundaries]] in the sense that they must respect the city government's ultimate authority over the land.\n<p>\nHowever, because the neighborhood wants to retain its authority and entitlements over the garden, especially against claims by the city government, residents are quite determined to [[Protect & Extend Value Sovereignty]]. They want to assure their long-term, quasi-independent authority over how the park shall be used. At the same time, they are committed to the garden being open to all. \n[[Use or Establish Discrimination-Free Infrastructures]] \n<p>\nIn a city where every square meter is potentially valuable on the real estate market, the Nidiaci garden is an impressive effort to [[Relationalize Property]] by showing that city spaces can be successfully be used and managed by the community. \n<p>\nTo make this work, there are various events in the life of the garden -- the children's football games, the exchange of used children's clothing, etc. -- that attempt to [[Ritualize Togetherness]].\n<p>\nIn bypassing the usual bureaucratic systems in a large urban government, the garden provides serious agency to ordinary people [Respect Human Dimensions]. Related to this, everyone can be part of the deliberations and decisionmaking [[Assure Commoners' Consent in Decisionmaking]]. As in most neighborhoods, information flows rather freely and there is a general openness about how responsibilities and entitlements are allocated. [[Share Knowledge Often & Widely]]; [[Honor Transparency in a Sphere of Trust]]\n<p>\nThere are few capital needs for the Nidiaci garden, but those tend to come from the city government. There has been no significant need to [[Self-Monitor, Mediate & Sanction]] in governing the Nidiaci Garden."
