    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
        "text": "The Nidiaci Community Garden is a strong and relatively rare example of a park managed directly and extensively by commoners. (Although, the [Potato Park] in Peru is another kind of \"park\" managed by commoners.) In their joint management of the Nidiaci garden, residents show their desire to [[Cultivate Shared Purpose & Values]]. They recognize that this is a collective enterprise that requires an [[Ubuntu-Rationality]] (although they don't use that term!).\n\n"
      },
      "date": 1512471772223
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
      "item": {
        "type": "html",
        "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
        "text": "There is no strict calculation of work performed with benefits received; the garden can only run if residents [[Contribute Freely]], [[Pool & Share]] or [[Pool, Cap & Divide Up]]. For instance, there are competing claims on the space at specific times, which residents need to deal with.  \n\nIn managing the garden, residents [[Practice Gentle Reciprocity]]. Activities are for free or, when costs must he paid, co-financed by voluntary contributions. By helping children spend time outdoors, one might say that the garden helps [[Deepen Interdependency on Nature]] in modest ways (which is certainly more necessary in a crowded city).    \n\n\nWhile the city administration might otherwise treat the park like any other city park, the ability of the neighborhood to manage their own garden reflects a willingness to [[Trust Situated Knowing]] and to [[Be Creatively Adaptive]]. The garden itself provides a space for parents to engage more fully with their children and with other parents -- i.e., to [[Honor Care & Time]].\n\n--More on [[Preserve Relationships in Addressing Conflicts]]"
      },
      "date": 1512471887622
    },
    {
      "item": {
        "type": "factory",
        "id": "5f3c7d4288d216fe"
      },
      "id": "5f3c7d4288d216fe",
