      "type": "edit",
      "id": "7376b9e77387253e",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "7376b9e77387253e",
        "text": "While much of the area is used as a playground, an important feature of the \"garden\" is that neighborhood residents themselves can decide how the space should be used. Some of those activities include:\n- Hosting the only self-managed football school in town, where children learn to enjoy playing and not\njust winning;\n- English lessons by a British writer;\n- Violin lessons by a Portuguese musician;\n- Open exchanges of children's clothes for free by parents, to avoid waste;\n- Managing a small community garden;\n- Work on monitoring pollution and traffic using equipment provided by the National Research Council;\n- singing lessons with an opera singer\n- the chance to organise birthday parties for children in a very cramped area, where parents have to pay considerable sums to rent space for parties\n- and much else."
      },
      "date": 1512472923284
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
      "item": {
        "type": "markdown",
        "id": "250887ea9ab807d5",
        "text": "The Nidiaci Community Garden is a strong and relatively rare european example of an inner-city park managed directly by commoners. In their joint management, residents show their desire to [[Cultivate Shared Purpose & Values]]. They recognize that this is a collective enterprise that requires an [[Ubuntu-Rationality]] (although they don't use that term).\n\n"
      },
      "date": 1512473004335
    },
    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
      "item": {
        "type": "html",
        "id": "4db93825b2d37094",
        "text": "There is no strict calculation of work performed with benefits received; the garden can only run if residents [[Contribute Freely]], [[Pool & Share]] or [[Pool, Cap & Divide Up]].There is a \"cap\", as there are sometimes competing claims on the space at specific times, which residents need to deal with.  \n\nIn managing the garden, residents [[Practice Gentle Reciprocity]]. Activities are for free or, when costs must he paid, co-financed by voluntary contributions. By helping children spend time outdoors, one might say that the garden helps [[Deepen Interdependency on Nature]] in modest ways (which is certainly more necessary in a crowded city).    \n\n\n\nWhile the city administration might otherwise treat the park like any other city park, the ability of the neighborhood to manage their own garden reflects a willingness to [[Trust Situated Knowing]] and to [[Be Creatively Adaptive]]. The garden itself provides a space for parents to engage more fully with their children and with other parents -- i.e., to [[Honor Care & Time]].\n"
      },
      "date": 1512476570827
